(27, 355, 'Aceh Tsunami Museum', 'aceh-tsunami-museum', '<p><span style="font-size: 10pt;"><strong>Aceh Tsunami Museum</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt;">Aceh Tsunami Museum is located on Sultan Iskandar Muda Street No. 3, Sukaramai, Baiturahman, Banda Aceh. This museum is designed as a symbolic reminiscene of the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami disaster, as well as an educational center and an emergency disaster shelter, in case the area is ever hit by a tsunami again. The Aceh Tsunami Museum was designed by Indonesian architect Ridwan Kamil. The museum is a 2,500 m<sup>2</sup> four-story structure, its long curving walls covered in geometric reliefs. Inside, visitors enter through a dark, narrow corridor between two high walls of water which is to recreate the noise and panic of the tsunami itself. The museum walls are adorned with images of people performing the Saman dance, a symbolic gesture dedicated to the strength, discipline and religious beliefs of the Acehnese people.  The roof resembles a tsunami from above. The ground floor is of traditional Acehnese house model that is best equipped to survive the tsunami. The exterior of the museum is to express cultural diversity of Aceh with decorative ornament element of transparency such as bamboo weaving. The interior view will lead you to the contemplation of the devastating disaster suffered by the people of Aceh as well surrender and recognition of the strength and power of God.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 10pt;">The building acknowledges both the victims, whose names are to be inscribed on the wall of one of the museum’s internal chambers, and the surviving members of the local community. In addition, its role as a memorial for those who died, the museum also offers a place of refuge from future such events, including an <em>escape hill</em> for visitors to run to in the event of another tsunami. There is tsunami showroom, pre-Tsunami, the day of the tsunami and post-tsunami space. Furthermore, a number of exhibitions at the museum include an electronic simulation of the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami, photographs of victims, diorama display and featuring stories from survivors of the disaster. There are some facilities such as space disaster painting, diorama, libraries, 4-dimensional space, as well as cafe.</span></p>\r\n<p>The Tsunami Aceh Museum additional information as following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The museum is open every day (except Friday)</li>\r\n<li>Phone : (0651) 40774</li>\r\n<li>The museum visit schedule</li>\r\n<li>Saturday 09.00-17.00</li>\r\n<li>Sunday 09.00-17.00</li>\r\n<li>Monday 09.00-17.00</li>\r\n<li>Tuesday 09.00-17.00</li>\r\n<li>Wednesday 09.00-17.00</li>\r\n<li>Thursday 09.00-17.00</li>\r\n</ul>', '', -2, 14, '2017-09-29 07:00:49', 959, '', '2017-09-29 07:00:49', 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2017-09-29 07:00:49', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{"image_intro":"","float_intro":"","image_intro_alt":"","image_intro_caption":"","image_fulltext":"","float_fulltext":"","image_fulltext_alt":"","image_fulltext_caption":""}', '{"urla":false,"urlatext":"","targeta":"","urlb":false,"urlbtext":"","targetb":"","urlc":false,"urlctext":"","targetc":""}', '{"article_layout":"","show_title":"","link_titles":"","show_tags":"","show_intro":"","info_block_position":"","info_block_show_title":"","show_category":"","link_category":"","show_parent_category":"","link_parent_category":"","show_associations":"","show_author":"","link_author":"","show_create_date":"","show_modify_date":"","show_publish_date":"","show_item_navigation":"","show_icons":"","show_print_icon":"","show_email_icon":"","show_vote":"","show_hits":"","show_noauth":"","urls_position":"","alternative_readmore":"","article_page_title":"","show_publishing_options":"","show_article_options":"","show_urls_images_backend":"","show_urls_images_frontend":""}', 1, 33, '', '', 1, 2, '{"robots":"","author":"","rights":"","xreference":""}', 0, '*', ''),
(28, 356, 'Alas River', 'alas-river', '<h1><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Alas River </strong></span></h1>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 10pt; color: #000000;">Alas River is the longest river in the province that passes through Gunung Lauser national park flowing up to the Indian Ocean. This river is located along the Southeast Aceh District, Gayo Lues District and South Aceh District. The name origin was derived from the tribe of Alas, the indigenous tribe who inhabit the Southeast Aceh District, this river crosses the entire land in the Alas community. While local people named it as <em>Lawe Alas</em> river.  The river is also situated at 165 km southeast Takengon, Alas River flows divides the Gunung Leuser National Park. This area is very popular among the young and adventurous. It has a sharp bend and the current challenging for the complainant guts. Those who are attracting to adrenalin rush, this river is suitable for rafting and many tourists come from all over the world.</span></p>', '', -2, 14, '2017-09-29 07:06:12', 959, '', '2017-09-29 07:06:12', 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2017-09-29 07:06:12', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{"image_intro":"","float_intro":"","image_intro_alt":"","image_intro_caption":"","image_fulltext":"","float_fulltext":"","image_fulltext_alt":"","image_fulltext_caption":""}', '{"urla":false,"urlatext":"","targeta":"","urlb":false,"urlbtext":"","targetb":"","urlc":false,"urlctext":"","targetc":""}', '{"article_layout":"","show_title":"","link_titles":"","show_tags":"","show_intro":"","info_block_position":"","info_block_show_title":"","show_category":"","link_category":"","show_parent_category":"","link_parent_category":"","show_associations":"","show_author":"","link_author":"","show_create_date":"","show_modify_date":"","show_publish_date":"","show_item_navigation":"","show_icons":"","show_print_icon":"","show_email_icon":"","show_vote":"","show_hits":"","show_noauth":"","urls_position":"","alternative_readmore":"","article_page_