(64, 1194, 'PANCASILA', 'pancasila1', '<h1>PANCASILA</h1>\r\n<p>Pancasila is the official philosophical foundation of the Indonesian state. The word Pancasila is derived from two Old Javanese words (originally from Sanskrit): "pañca" meaning five, and "sīla" meaning principles.</p>\r\n<p>It comprises five principles held to be inseparable and interrelated:<br />1.    Ketuhanan Yang Maha Esa)- -Belief in the absoluteness of God.<br />2.    Kemanusiaan Yang Adil dan Beradab) - Just and civilised humanity.<br />3.    Persatuan Indonesia - The unity of Indonesia (in Indonesian.<br />4.    Kerakyatan Yang Dipimpin oleh Hikmat Kebijaksanaan, Dalam Permusyawaratan Perwakilan  - Democracy guided by the inner wisdom in the unanimity arising out of deliberations amongst representatives.<br />5.    Keadilan Sosial bagi seluruh Rakyat Indonesia  - Social justice for all of the people of Indonesia (in Indonesian.</p>\r\n<p>The Constitution of Indonesia of 1945 defined the Pancasila as the fundamental principles of the independent Indonesian state. It was further interpreted by the New Order Administration under the second President of Indonesia, Suharto to mean:</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em>Pancasila democracy endeavours to strike a balance between the interests of the individual and those of society. It seeks to prevent the oppression of the weak by the strong, whether by economic or political means. Therefore, we hold that Pancasila is a socio-religious society. Briefly its major characteristics are its rejection of poverty, backwardness, conflicts, exploitation, capitalism, feudalism, dictatorship, colonialism and imperialism. This is the policy I have chosen with confidence.</em></p>\r\n<p>Pancasila is still taught in schools and supported by the Government and people as the foundation stone of the Indonesian State.</p>\r\n<p> </p>', '', 1, 209, '2017-10-04 08:15:39', 958, '', '2017-10-05 02:58:57', 959, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2017-10-04 08:15:39', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{"image_intro":"images\\/frontpage_images\\/articles\\/Indonesia - CoA_small_1.jpg","float_intro":"","image_intro_alt":"","image_intro_caption":"","image_fulltext":"","float_fulltext":"","image_fulltext_alt":"","image_fulltext_caption":""}', '{"urla":false,"urlatext":"","targeta":"","urlb":false,"urlbtext":"","targetb":"","urlc":false,"urlctext":"","targetc":""}', '{"article_layout":"","show_title":"","link_titles":"","show_tags":"","show_intro":"","info_block_position":"","info_block_show_title":"","show_category":"","link_category":"","show_parent_category":"","link_parent_category":"","show_associations":"","show_author":"","link_author":"","show_create_date":"","show_modify_date":"","show_publish_date":"","show_item_navigation":"","show_icons":"","show_print_icon":"","show_email_icon":"","show_vote":"","show_hits":"","show_noauth":"","urls_position":"","alternative_readmore":"","article_page_title":"","show_publishing_options":"","show_article_options":"","show_urls_images_backend":"","show_urls_images_frontend":""}', 20, 1, '', '', 1, 64, '{"robots":"","author":"","rights":"","xreference":""}', 0, '*', ''),
(65, 1538, 'MAJOR CITIES', 'major-cities', '<h1>MAJOR CITIES</h1>\r\n<p>There are many cities in Indonesia with more than a million people. This is a list of the more significant ones</p>\r\n', '\r\n<p>,but there are many others to explore throughout the archipelago.</p>\r\n<p>Jakarta — with over 9 million people, Indonesia''s capital is the largest city in the country. It sits on the northwest coast of Java. Tourists enjoy a vast number of attractions including its long history and diverse architecture, language and cuisine; influenced by hundreds of years of mixing of cultures such as Javanese, Malay, Chinese, Arab, Indian and European. To list just a few points of interest: the old town, Kota Tua, is home to Dutch colonial buildings, Glodok (Jakarta’s Chinatown) and the old port of Sunda Kelapa.</p>\r\n<p>Surabaya — is the capital of East Java and Indonesia’s second biggest city. It sits on the north coast with a busy port and acts as the gateway to the island of Madura. It is a vibrant, sprawling city with a mix modern skyscrapers and substantial buildings from its Dutch colonial past. Key points of interest include: a thriving Chinatown and Arab quarter featuring the 15th century Ampel Mosque; and the Tugu Pahlawan (Heroes Monument) honouring the independence battles that waged in Surabaya’s streets in 1945</p>\r\n<p><br />Bandung — is the capital of West Java Province and third largest city in Indonesia. It is a university town set the cooler highlands of Java surrounded by volcanoes and tea plantations. It''s known for its colonial and art deco buildings, a lively, university-town feel and cooler tropical weather. Key points of interest include: fashion outlets clustered along Jalan Setiabudi and Jalan Riau in the Dago district., many architectural jewels including Villa Isola, Gedung Merdeka and Cipaganti Mosque by colonial Dutch architect C.P.W. Shoemakers, Bandung Zoo, Kawah Putih crater and any number of tea plantations</p>\r\n<p><br />Yogyakarta —Jojga as it commonly known played pivotal role in the creation of the Indonesian Republic resulting in it being granted Special Administrative Region status, making it the only region headed by a monarchy in Indonesia. It is Java''s artistic and cultural hub and well used by tourists, accessing the mighty ancient temples of Prambanan and Borobudur. Other points of interest include: the Kraton - Sultan''s palace in the centre of the city; the Taman Sari water castle and nearby Mount Merapi</p>\r\n<p><br />Semarang — is the capital of Central Java. It is a major port city on the central north coast of Java with a long history of blending Javanese, Chinese, and Dutch influences. Key points of interest include the old Dutch quarter with many landmarks such as Lawang Sewu, the massive railway company headquarters. Also of interest is Sam Poo Kong, a 15th-century temple, in Chinatown. At the heart of the commercial district is the Simpang Lima, a beautiful tree-lined green space</p>\r\n<p><br />Banda Aceh – capital of Aceh Province and the most northern city in Indonesia. Key points of Interest are the Baiturrahman Grand Mosque and Tsunami Museum that commemorates the devastating tsunami that killed over 200,000 people in 2004</p>\r\n<p><br />Medan – capital of North Sumatra and Indonesia’s fourth largest city. Points of interest are the Istana Maimun (Maimoon Palace), Great Mosque of Medan, Tjong A Fie Mansion, Indo-Moghul Catholic church of Graha Maria Annai Velangkanni , Jalan Selat Panjang street, famous for its ethnic food stalls</p>\r\n<p><br />Padang — the capital of West Sumatra province, it lies on Sumatra''s west coast. Key points of interest include: the old quarter around the Batang Arau port and river where you can find Dutch colonial buildings and fishing boats; the Museum Adityawarman, a distinctive, traditional curved-roof structure set in park-like grounds, that has a vast collection of regional artifacts; and the lovely Pantai Air Manis – a great place to watch the sunset</p>\r\n<p><br />Pekanbaru — the capital of Riau Province, it is an inland city on the bank of the Siak River that flows East into the Straits of Malacca. Points of interest include the provincial cultural and heritage museum Sang Nila Utama Museum; the  Great Mosque of An-Nur; the historic Great Mosque of Pekanbaru; two modern Malay architecture buildings – the Idrus Tintin (MTQ) Building and  Soeman H.S. County Library; and a number of nice parks</p>\r\n<p><br />Kota Jambi — the capital of Jambi Province; situated in southern Sumatra. It is one of the access points to Gunung Kerinci, the highest active volcano in Indonesia that last erupted in 2009. Other points of interest include: Muaro Jambi, Sumatra''s largest archaeological site that was the seat of the Melayu Kingdom in the 4th-13th centuries; Bukit Duabelas National Park, one of the last remaining lowland rainforests in Sumatra and home to the nomadic Orang Rimba tribe; and Taman Tanggo Rajo alongside Sungai Batanghari river bank</p>\r\n<p><br />Palembang — the capital of South Sumatra, is a port city on the Musi River. Key points of interest include: the Ampera Bridge, the palatial Museum Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II, the sacred hill Bukit Siguntang,  a floating market and houses on stilts on the river’s edge.</p>', 1, 209, '2017-10-05 09:49:46', 958, '', '2017-10-06 04:37:06', 958, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2017-10-05 09:49:46', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{"image_intro":"images\\/frontpage_images\\/articles\\/Major Cities.jpg","float_intro":"","image_intro_alt":"","image_intro_caption":"","image_fulltext":"","float_fulltext":"","image_fulltext_alt":"","image_fulltext_caption":""}', '{"urla":false,"urlatext":"","targeta":"","urlb":false,"urlbtext":"","targetb":"","urlc":false,"urlctext":"","targetc":""}', '{"article_layout":"","show_title":"","link_titles":"","show_tags":"","show_intro":"","info_block_position":"","info_block_show_title":"","show_category":"","link_category":"","show_parent_category":"","link_parent_category":"","show_associations":"","show_author":"","link_author":"","show_create_date":"","show_modify_date":"","show_publish_date":"","show_item_navigation":"","show_icons":"","show_print_icon":"","show_email_icon":"","show_vote":"","show_hits":"","show_noauth":"","urls_position":"","alternative_readmore":"","article_page_title":"","show_publishing_options":"","show_article_options":"","show_urls_images_backend":"","show_urls_images_frontend":""}', 8, 0, '', '', 1, 7, '{"robots":"","author":"","rights":"","xreference":""}', 0, '*', ''),
(66, 1539, 'ECONOMY', 'economy', '<p>Indonesia, the largest economy in Southeast Asia, has seen a slowdown in growth since 2012, mostly due to the end of the commodities export boom.</p>\r\n', '\r\n<p>During the global financial crisis, Indonesia outperformed its regional neighbors and joined China and India as the only G20 members posting growth. Indonesia’s annual budget deficit is capped at 3% of GDP, and the Government of Indonesia lowered its debt-to-GDP ratio from a peak of 100% shortly after the Asian financial crisis in 1999 to less than 27 percent today. While Fitch and Moody''s Investors upgraded Indonesia''s credit rating to investment grade in December 2011, Standard &amp; Poor’s has yet to raise Indonesia’s rating to this status amid several constraints to foreign direct investment in the country, such as a high level of protectionism.</p>\r\n<p>Indonesia still struggles with poverty and unemployment, inadequate infrastructure, corruption, a complex regulatory environment, and unequal resource distribution among its regions. President Joko WIDODO - elected in July 2014 – seeks to develop Indonesia’s maritime resources and pursue other infrastructure development, including significantly increasing its electrical power generation capacity. Fuel subsidies were significantly reduced in early 2015, a move which has helped the government redirect its spending to development priorities. Indonesia, with the nine other ASEAN members, will continue to move towards participation in the ASEAN Economic Community, though full implementation of economic integration has not yet materialized.</p>', 1, 209, '2017-10-05 10:22:24', 958, '', '2017-10-06 04:25:14', 958, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2017-10-05 10:22:24', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{"image_intro":"images\\/frontpage_images\\/articles\\/Economy.jpg","float_intro":"","image_intro_alt":"","image_intro_caption":"","image_fulltext":"","float_fulltext":"","image_fulltext_alt":"","image_fulltext_caption":""}', '{"urla":false,"urlatext":"","targeta":"","urlb":false,"urlbtext":"","targetb":"","urlc":false,"urlctext":"","targetc":""}', '{"article_layout":"","show_title":"","link_titles":"","show_tags":"","show_intro":"","info_block_position":"","info_block_show_title":"","show_category":"","link_category":"","show_parent_category":"","link_parent_category":"","show_associations":"","show_author":"","link_author":"","show_create_date":"","show_modify_date":"","show_publish_date":"","show_item_navigation":"","show_icons":"","show_print_icon":"","show_email_icon":"","show_vote":"","show_hits":"","show_noauth":"","urls_position":"","alternative_readmore":"","article_page_title":"","show_publishing_options":"","show_article_options":"","show_urls_images_backend":"","show_urls_images_frontend":""}', 4, 0, '', '', 1, 3, '{"robots":"","author":"","rights":"","xreference":""}', 0, '*', ''),
(67, 1630, 'QUICK FACTS', 'quick-facts', '<h1>QUICK FACTS</h1>\r\n<p>Here are some quick facts about Indonesia''s location, geography, people, government, economy education and much more.</p>\r\n', '\r\n<p><strong>LOCATION</strong><br /> Southeastern Asia, archipelago between the Indian and Pacific oceans</p>\r\n<p><strong>GEOGRAPHIC COORDINATES</strong><br /> 5 00 S, 120 00 E</p>\r\n<p><strong>AREA</strong> - 16<sup>th</sup> largest country in the World<br /> Total: 1,904,569 sq km<br /> Land: 1,811,569 sq km<br /> <strong>T</strong>he country straddles the equator and occupies a strategic location astride or along major sea lanes from the Indian Ocean to the Pacific Ocean. Despite having the fourth largest population in the world, Indonesia is the most heavily forested region on earth after the Amazon</p>\r\n<p><strong>CLIMATE</strong><br /> Tropical,  hot and humid; cooler in highlands</p>\r\n<p><strong>TERRAIN</strong><br /> Mostly coastal lowlands; larger islands have tropical rainforests, mountains and some active volcanoes<br /> <strong>Highest point:</strong> Puncak Jaya 4,884 m, Papua Province</p>\r\n<p><strong>NATURAL RESOURCES</strong><br /> Petroleum, tin, natural gas, nickel, timber, bauxite, copper, fertile soils, coal, gold, silver</p>\r\n<p><strong>LAND USE</strong><br /> Agricultural land: 31.2%<br /> Irrigated land:  67,220 sq km (2012)<br /> Arable land 13%; permanent crops 12.1%; permanent pasture 6.1%<br /> Forest: 51.7%<br /> Other: 17.1% (2011 est.)</p>\r\n<p><strong>NATURAL HAZARDS</strong><br /> Occasional floods; severe droughts; tsunamis; earthquakes; volcanic eruptions and  forest fires. Indonesia contains the most volcanoes of any country in the world - some 76 have been active in recent times. Significant volcanic activity occurs on Java, Sumatra, the Sunda Islands including Bali and Lombok, Halmahera Island, Sulawesi Island, Sangihe Island, and in the Banda Sea; Merapi (elev. 2,968 m), Indonesia''s most active volcano that last erupted in 2010. Other notable historically active volcanoes include Agung, Awu, Karangetang, Krakatoa, Makian, Raung, and Tambora.</p>\r\n<p><strong>ENVIRONMENT ISSUES</strong><br /> Deforestation; water pollution from industrial wastes, sewage; air pollution in urban areas; smoke and haze from forest fires</p>\r\n<p><strong>ENVIRONMENT - INTERNATIONAL AGREEMENTS</strong><br /> Party to: Biodiversity, Climate Change, Climate Change-Kyoto Protocol, Desertification, Endangered Species, Hazardous Wastes, Law of the Sea, Ozone Layer Protection, Ship Pollution, Tropical Timber 83, Tropical Timber 94, Wetlands<br /> Signed, but not ratified: Marine Life Conservation</p>\r\n<hr class="system-pagebreak" />\r\n<p><strong>POPULATION -  </strong>4<sup>th</sup> largest country in the World<br /> 260,580,739  (July 2017 est.)<br /> Main concentration on the island of Java, which is one of the most densely populated places on earth; Sumatra contains some of the most significant clusters, particularly in the south near the Selat Sunda, and along the northeastern coast near Medan. The cities of Makassar (Sulawesi), Banjarmasin (Kalimantan) are also heavily populated.</p>\r\n<p><strong>ETHNIC GROUPS</strong><br /> Javanese 40.1%, Sundanese 15.5%, Malay 3.7%, Batak 3.6%, Madurese 3%, Betawi 2.9%, Minangkabau 2.7%, Buginese 2.7%, Bantenese 2%, Banjarese 1.7%, Balinese 1.7%, Acehnese 1.4%, Dayak 1.4%, Sasak 1.3%, Chinese 1.2%, other 15% (2010 est.)</p>\r\n<p><strong>LANGUAGES</strong><br /> Bahasa Indonesia (official, modified form of Malay), English, Dutch, local dialects (of which the most widely spoken is Javanese). More than 700 languages are used in Indonesia</p>\r\n<p>R<strong>ELIGIONS<br /> </strong>Muslim 87.2%, Protestant 7%, Roman Catholic 2.9%, Hindu 1.7%, other 0.9% (includes Buddhist and Confucian), unspecified 0.4% (2010 est.)</p>\r\n<p><strong>AGE STRUCTURE </strong>(2017 est.)<br /> 0-14 years: 25.02% (male 33,205,805/female 31,994,844)<br /> 15-24 years: 16.99% (male 22,537,842/female 21,738,210)<br /> 25-54 years: 42.4% (male 56,493,414/female 53,980,979)<br /> 55-64 years: 8.58% (male 10,192,430/female 12,177,931)<br /> 65 years and over: 7.01% (male 7,954,795/female 10,304,489)</p>\r\n<p><strong>MEDIAN AGE </strong>(2016 est.)<br /> Total: 29.9 years<br /> Male: 29.3 years<br /> Female: 30.5 years</p>\r\n<p><strong>POPULATION GROWTH RATE</strong> (2017 est.)<br /> 0.9%</p>\r\n<p><strong>BIRTH RATE</strong> (2017 est.)<br /> 16.2 births/1,000 population</p>\r\n<p><strong>DEATH RATE</strong> (2017 est.)<br /> 6.5 deaths/1,000 population (2017 est.)</p>\r\n<p><strong>NET MIGRATION RATE</strong> (2017 est.)<br /> -1.1 migrant(s)/1,000 population (2017 est.)</p>\r\n<p><strong>URBANIZATION</strong> (2017 est.)<br /> Urban population: 55.2% of total population<br /> Rate of urbanization: 2.3% annual rate of change (2015 est.)</p>\r\n<p><strong>MAJOR POPULATION CENTRES</strong> (2015)<br /> JAKARTA (capital) 10.323 million; Surabaya 2.853 million; Bandung 2.544 million; Medan 2.204 million; Semarang 1.63 million; Makassar 1.489 million (2015)</p>\r\n<p><strong>LIFE EXPECTANCY AT BIRTH</strong> (2016 est.)<br /> Total population: 72.7 years<br /> Male: 70.1 years<br /> Female: 75.5 years</p>\r\n<hr class="system-pagebreak" />\r\n<p><strong>HEALTH EXPENDITURES</strong> (2014)<br /> 2.8% of GDP</p>\r\n<p><strong>HIV/AIDS</strong> - <br /> 0.4% - adult prevalence rate (2016 est.)<br /> 620,000 people living with HIV/AIDS (2016 est.)<br /> 38,000 deaths (2016 est.)</p>\r\n<p><strong>MAJOR INFECTIOUS DISEASES</strong><br /> Degree of risk: very high<br /> Food or waterborne diseases: bacterial diarrhea, hepatitis A, and typhoid fever<br /> Vector-borne diseases: dengue fever and malaria (2016)</p>\r\n<p><strong>OBESITY</strong> <br /> 5.7% - adult prevalence rate (2014)<br /> Children under the age of 5 years underweight:  19.9% (2013)</p>\r\n<p><strong>EDUCATION EXPENDITURES</strong><br /> 3.3% of GDP (2014)</p>\r\n<p><strong>LITERACY </strong>(2016 est.)<br /> Definition: age 15 and over can read and write<br /> Total population: 95.4%<br /> Male: 97.2%<br /> Female: 93.6%</p>\r\n<p><strong>PERIOD OF TIME AT SCHOOL</strong> (2014)<br /> Total: 13 years<br /> Male: 13 years<br /> Female: 13 years</p>\r\n<p><strong>CHILD LABOUR</strong> - children ages 5-14 (2009 est.)<br /> Total number: 4,026,285 (7%)</p>\r\n<p><strong>YOUTH UNEMPLOYMENT</strong> -- youth ages 15-24 (2015 est.)<br /> Total: 22.6%<br /> Male: 22.3%<br /> Female: 23.1%</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>', 1, 209, '2017-10-06 03:40:21', 958, '', '2017-10-06 06:57:56', 958, 958, '2017-10-06 07:05:33', '2017-10-06 03:40:21', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{"image_intro":"images\\/frontpage_images\\/articles\\/Indonesia.jpg","float_intro":"","image_intro_alt":"","image_intro_caption":"","image_fulltext":"","float_fulltext":"","image_fulltext_alt":"","image_fulltext_caption":""}', '{"urla":false,"urlatext":"","targeta":"","urlb":false,"urlbtext":"","targetb":"","urlc":false,"urlctext":"","targetc":""}', '{"article_layout":"","show_title":"","link_titles":"","show_tags":"","show_intro":"","info_block_position":"","info_block_show_title":"","show_category":"","link_category":"","show_parent_category":"","link_parent_category":"","show_associations":"","show_author":"","link_author":"","show_create_date":"","show_modify_date":"","show_publish_date":"","show_item_navigation":"","show_icons":"","show_print_icon":"","show_email_icon":"","show_vote":"","show_hits":"","show_noauth":"","urls_position":"","alternative_readmore":"","article_page_title":"","show_publishing_options":"","show_article_options":"","show_urls_images_backend":"","show_urls_images_frontend":""}', 12, 0, '', '', 1, 18, '{"robots":"","author":"","rights":"","xreference":""}', 0, '*', '');
