(436, 23, 1, '', '2017-09-29 04:29:51', 957, 6392, '36219ada5474eb0c40854366167198fb89a56e03', '{"id":23,"asset_id":348,"title":"Batam Dragon Fruit Agro Tourism","alias":"batam-dragon-fruit-agro-tourism","introtext":"<p>Batam Dragon Fruit Agro Tourism becomes an intriguing alternative choice for holiday makers particularly to those who have been mundane with\\u00a0 daily routine. Visiting Batam without tasting fresh pick dragon fruit will probably be considered an incomplete visit. This fruit becomes one of the typical fruits of Batam City. Along the Trans Barelang road, particularly around Rempang and Galang, there are dragon fruit plantation. Two prominent farms are Naga Zore and Dragon Fruit Orchards. Naga Zone has an area of approximately 4 hectares. \\u00a0While. Dragon Fruit Orchards in this region is covering an area of 105 acres are managed by 36 farmers scattered in several locations. The background scenery of its dragon fruit farm is exquisite sea. Entourage of tourists can relax at the cafe in farm area enjoying fresh dragon fruit juice, dragon fruit soup, dragon fruit sticks and so forth in a blue sea panoramic which is decorated behind the dragon fruit plantation.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>In addition to directly feel the fresh of dragon fruit juice, tourists can also pick directly from the tree. If you want to pluck straight from the tree must order before Friday owing to the farmers will harvest every Friday to stock up on Saturday and Sunday. The dragon fruit is sold at Rp 40,000 per kilogram which is cheaper than in any supermarket.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h2><strong>The Story of Dragon Fruit<\\/strong><\\/h2>\\r\\n<p>Dragon fruit is the fruit of several cactus species of the genera Hylocereus and Selenicereus. This fruit comes from Mexico, Central America and South America but is now also cultivated in Asian countries like Taiwan, Vietnam, Philippines, Indonesia and Malaysia. This fruit can also be found in Okinawa, Israel, Northern Australia and southern China. Hylocereus blooms only at night. In United Kingdom, Dragon fruit\\u00a0 is well-known as <em>Pitaya<\\/em>.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>In 1870 this plant was brought from Guiana French people to Vietnam as an ornamental plant. By the Vietnamese and Chinese men are considered a blessing. Therefore, the fruit is always placed between two green dragon tail statues above the altar table. Red fruit color stand out among the green dragons. This is the fruit of a habit among the Vietnamese people are much inuenced Chinese culture known as the Thang Loy (dragon fruit). The term Thang Loy then translated in Europe and other countries who speak English as a dragon fruit<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>In addition to the sweet taste refreshing, dragon fruit is rich in benets. Many people believe this fruit can lower cholesterol and balance blood sugar. There has been no research on the benets of this fruit, but because the origin of species believed to dragon fruit cactus fruit contains vitamin C, beta carotene, calcium, and carbohydrates. Dragon fruit contains high ber as a binder cancer-causing carcinogen and facilitate the digestive process.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h2><strong>Additional Information<\\/strong><\\/h2>\\r\\n<table width=\\"0\\">\\r\\n<tbody>\\r\\n<tr>\\r\\n<td width=\\"23%\\">\\r\\n<p>Location<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>:<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>Rempang Island (after Barelang Bridge IV)<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<\\/tr>\\r\\n<tr>\\r\\n<td width=\\"23%\\">\\r\\n<p>Telephone<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>:<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>+62 811 691274, +62819 800007<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<\\/tr>\\r\\n<tr>\\r\\n<td width=\\"23%\\">\\r\\n<p>Opening hours<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>:<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>weekdays, 9am-5pm; weekend and public holidays, 9am-6:30pm<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<\\/tr>\\r\\n<tr>\\r\\n<td width=\\"23%\\">\\r\\n<p>Admission fee<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>:<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>free<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<\\/tr>\\r\\n<tr>\\r\\n<td width=\\"23%\\">\\r\\n<p>Facilities<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>:<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>restaurant, tour guide (only in Bahasa Indonesia)<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<\\/tr>\\r\\n<tr>\\r\\n<td width=\\"23%\\">\\r\\n<p>Remarks<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>:<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<td>\\r\\n<p>you need give them prior notification, at least 2 days before coming. It is usually will be crowded on weekends and public holidays. Since there is no ATMs along Trans Barelang, it might be better to have some cash money with you.<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/td>\\r\\n<\\/tr>\\r\\n<\\/tbody>\\r\\n<\\/table>\\r\\n<p><strong>\\u00a0<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<h2><strong>How to get there<\\/strong><\\/h2>\\r\\n<p>It is located in the 4<sup>th<\\/sup> Barelang Bridge, precisely three \\u00a0islands after leaving \\u00a0the mainland of Batam. There you will see the dragon fruit gardens which extend to the neat. From the downtown (Batam Centre), it will take approximately 50 minutes, depend from where you are departed<\\/p>","fulltext":"","state":1,"catid":"2","created":"2017-09-29 04:29:51","created_by":"957","created_by_alias":"","modified":"2017-09-29 04:29:51","modified_by":null,"checked_out":null,"checked_out_time":null,"publish_up":"2017-09-29 04:29:51","publish_down":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","images":"{\\"image_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"float_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_caption\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"float_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_caption\\":\\"\\"}","urls":"{\\"urla\\":false,\\"urlatext\\":\\"\\",\\"targeta\\":\\"\\",\\"urlb\\":false,\\"urlbtext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetb\\":\\"\\",\\"urlc\\":false,\\"urlctext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetc\\":\\"\\"}","attribs":"{\\"article_layout\\":\\"\\",\\"show_title\\":\\"\\",\\"link_titles\\":\\"\\",\\"show_tags\\":\\"\\",\\"show_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"info_block_position\\":\\"\\",\\"info_block_show_title\\":\\"\\",\\"show_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_associations\\":\\"\\",\\"show_author\\":\\"\\",\\"link_author\\":\\"\\",\\"show_create_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_modify_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publish_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_item_navigation\\":\\"\\",\\"show_icons\\":\\"\\",\\"show_print_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_email_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_vote\\":\\"\\",\\"show_hits\\":\\"\\",\\"show_noauth\\":\\"\\",\\"urls_position\\":\\"\\",\\"alternative_readmore\\":\\"\\",\\"article_page_title\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publishing_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_article_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_backend\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_frontend\\":\\"\\"}","version":1,"ordering":null,"metakey":"","metadesc":"","access":"1","hits":null,"metadata":"{\\"robots\\":\\"\\",\\"author\\":\\"\\",\\"rights\\":\\"\\",\\"xreference\\":\\"\\"}","featured":"0","language":"*","xreference":""}', 0),
(437, 24, 1, '', '2017-09-29 04:34:18', 959, 9622, 'a96e4765df4b217916a4fd98890776c8ad9f999e', '{"id":24,"asset_id":349,"title":"Aceh","alias":"aceh","introtext":"<p><strong>Aceh<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Aceh is world famous for bearing the brunt of the worst tsunami in recorded history in the early hours of Boxing Day 2004 in which over 200,000 people died. However, this is the most western of Indonesia\\u2019s provinces that has a long and rich culture. Its strategic position at the most western point of the Indonesian archipelago has made it a trade and cultural gateway between East and West for many centuries. Aceh is often prominently known as a haven for Chinese, European, Indian and Arab traders, where the first cultural and religious value immersed in the archipelago. The name of Aceh is an acronym of Arab, Chinese, European and Hindustan (ACEH).<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Provincial Structure<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The province of Aceh is the most northern and western province of Indonesia, situated on the northern tip of Sumatra. Its capital city is Banda Aceh. Administratively, Aceh consists of 18 districts, 5 municipalities, 289 subdistricts and 6.474 gampong (villages) with an area of 57.956 km<sup>2<\\/sup>. There is a unity of the legal community within the province consisting of a few <em>gampong <\\/em>that have territorial boundaries with their own property and sub-district called <em>Mukim<\\/em>, for each <em>Mukim<\\/em> led by <em>Imum Mukim <\\/em>(customary leader).<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Geography<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The province of Aceh is situated in the North of Sumatra, with an area of approximately 57,365 km<sup>2<\\/sup>, or 12.26% of the Sumatra Island. It includes 119 islands, 73 major rivers and 2 lakes. Aceh is surrounded by the Straits of Malacca in the north, North Sumatra Province in the Southeast and the Indian Ocean in the west.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The center of this westward extansion area is a range of Bukit Barisan and various highlands including Tangse, Gayo and Alas. Besides the cluster of Pase mountains, there are Mount Geurudong (2,295 m), Peuet Sagoe (2,780 m), Burni Telong (2,566 m) and Ucop Mulo (3,187 m). In the Alas mountains, there are Mount Abong (3,015 m) and Leuser (3,466 m). In the mountainous region of Aceh Besar, there are two peaks of Mount Seulawah Agam (1762 m) and Seulawah Inong (868 m).<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The area also has several lakes such as Lake Laut Tawar in Central Aceh with an area of 60 km<sup>2<\\/sup> and Lake Aneuk Laot in Sabang (Weh Island). There are also several major and lesser rivers, which run into both of Malacca Strait or the Indonesian Ocean. Among the rivers running into Malacca Straits are: Krueng Aceh (Aceh River) in the Greater Aceh Regency, Krueng Peusangan and Krueng Jambo Aye in North Aceh Regency, Krueng Baro in Pidie Regency, and Krueng Peureulak and Krueng Tamiang in East Aceh Regency; The rivers running to the Indonesian Qcean are Krueng Teunom and Krueng Meureubo in West Aceh Regency, Krueng Kluet, Krueng Simpang Kiri and Krueng Simpang Kanan in South Aceh Regency. On the west and south coasts, there are both large and small islands, some of which are inhabited and others, which are uninhabited. These islands are Weh Island, Breuh Island, Nasi Island, Simeulue Island and Tuangke Island.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>There are a number of major towns, among them: <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikivoyage.org\\/wiki\\/Banda_Aceh\\">Banda Aceh<\\/a> (capital), <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikivoyage.org\\/wiki\\/Lhokseumawe\\">Lhokseumawe<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikivoyage.org\\/wiki\\/Meulaboh\\">Meulaboh<\\/a>, Sigli, and Calang. Also the island of <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikivoyage.org\\/wiki\\/Sabang_%28Indonesia%29\\">Sabang<\\/a> (an hour ferry ride from <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikivoyage.org\\/wiki\\/Banda_Aceh\\">Banda Aceh<\\/a>) is considered as diver''s and snorkeler''s pristine paradise belongs to the province.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>How to get there <\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Visa<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Foreigners no longer require a travel permit (<em>Surat Jalan<\\/em>) to enter Aceh, but an Indonesian visa is required if their country origin is not on the list of 169 Receiving Visa Free Countries. Furthermore, Since 6 June 2010, it is possible to get a 30 days Visa-on-Arrival at Banda Aceh Airport.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3><span style=\\"color: #000000;\\">By bus<\\/span><\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>There are non-stop night buses depart from Medan to Banda Aceh and it takes 9-13 hours. Major bus companies such as PMTOH, Pelangi, Kurnia and Pusaka have offices on Jl. Gajah Mada, Medan.\\u00a0 The price ranges from Rp 110,000 in a regular-sized-seat bus to Rp 200,000 in a wide-seat bus. Mini-buses can also take you to Banda Aceh from the Medan area. It will cost you a bit cheaper thatn the coaches but the trip are generally longer. It is also possible to depart from Medan to Banda Aceh via Kutacane and Takengon. This will take 20 hours.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>By Plane <\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Sultan Iskandar Muda Airport (BTJ) is the name of airport located in the capital of Aceh Province. The Airlines schedule fly daily from Banda Aceh to Medan (1 hour trip) and either Jakarta (2 hours 40 minutes trip) and vice versa.<\\/p>\\r\\n<ol>\\r\\n<li>Air Asia, Banda Aceh-Kuala Lumpur (vice versa) daily flights<\\/li>\\r\\n<li>Firefly, Malaysia''s community airline now flies from Penang to Banda Aceh every Tuesday, Thursday and Saturday<\\/li>\\r\\n<li>Garuda Indonesia, Citilink, Lion Air, Batik Air, Jakarta-Banda Aceh (vice versa) daily flights<\\/li>\\r\\n<li>SMAC, Blang Pidie, Meulaboh, Simelue, Takengon, Tapaktuan. It flies daily from Medan to Nias Island and Simeulue Island.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ol>\\r\\n<p><strong>Airport Bus<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>A DAMRI bus provides a service from Banda A\\u0441eh to the airport, and from the airport to Banda Aceh. It has operating hours at 10 a.m - 4.30 p.m and the price to the city is Rp 20,000 per person. The bus departing from the airport to Banda A\\u0441eh leaves a few minutes after the airplanes landing. Therefore, departure time depends on airplanes\\u2019 landing schedule. Thus, it is advised to hurry to catch the bus. It is on your left when you leave the airport building (taxi drivers will tell you there is no airport bus, just keep on walking because the bus is there). Please note that this bus goes to Banda Aceh City Centre, it does not go to the Bus Station or Ulee-Lhue Harbour. If you want to go to the Bus Station or Ulee-Lhue Harbour, take a <em>becak <\\/em>(traditional ground vehicle) after being dropped off in the City Centre by the airport bus. To go to the airport, you can catch the bus at 8 am, 2 pm or 3 pm in front of the Great Mosque of Banda Aceh or Masjid Baiturahman.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>By Boat<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The closest international ferry terminal is Belawan Port, close to Medan. It receives vessels originating from Batam Island. Entourage of tourists can also depart from Ulhee-lhee Port (Banda Aceh) to Weh Island and Aceh Island.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Get Around<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The main vehicle of getting around are <em>becak<\\/em> (motorbike taxis) and <em>labi-labi<\\/em> (public minibus). Both pblic transportation will cost you, becak fares are Airport - Grand Mosque is Rp 40,000,\\u00a0 Bus Terminal - Grand Mosque is Rp 8,000, Grand Mosque \\u2013 Penayong is Rp 5,000.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Additional Information<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>There are approximately 65 NGOs currently operating in Banda Aceh.\\u00a0 However, they generally do not recruit non-Indonesians. These NGOs include various UN and EU agencies, USNS, Care, Americare, Islamic Relief, International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent, Australian Red Cross, Turkish Red Crescent, Kuwaiti Red Crescent, French Red Cross, IMC, IOM, WHO, Japan International Cooperation System, Habitat, Medecins sans fronti\\u00e8res, Japan Platform, USAID. At the peak of the post-Tsunami aid effort there were 850 NGOs, but many of these were non-Muslim religious organisations and their permits were not extended by the Indonesian government.<\\/p>","fulltext":"","state":1,"catid":"14","created":"2017-09-29 04:34:18","created_by":"959","created_by_alias":"","modified":"2017-09-29 04:34:18","modified_by":null,"checked_out":null,"checked_out_time":null,"publish_up":"2017-09-29 04:34:18","publish_down":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","images":"{\\"image_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"float_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_caption\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"float_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_caption\\":\\"\\"}","urls":"{\\"urla\\":false,\\"urlatext\\":\\"\\",\\"targeta\\":\\"\\",\\"urlb\\":false,\\"urlbtext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetb\\":\\"\\",\\"urlc\\":false,\\"urlctext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetc\\":\\"\\"}","attribs":"{\\"article_layout\\":\\"\\",\\"show_title\\":\\"\\",\\"link_titles\\":\\"\\",\\"show_tags\\":\\"\\",\\"show_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"info_block_position\\":\\"\\",\\"info_block_show_title\\":\\"\\",\\"show_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_associations\\":\\"\\",\\"show_author\\":\\"\\",\\"link_author\\":\\"\\",\\"show_create_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_modify_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publish_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_item_navigation\\":\\"\\",\\"show_icons\\":\\"\\",\\"show_print_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_email_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_vote\\":\\"\\",\\"show_hits\\":\\"\\",\\"show_noauth\\":\\"\\",\\"urls_position\\":\\"\\",\\"alternative_readmore\\":\\"\\",\\"article_page_title\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publishing_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_article_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_backend\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_frontend\\":\\"\\"}","version":1,"ordering":null,"metakey":"","metadesc":"","access":"1","hits":null,"metadata":"{\\"robots\\":\\"\\",\\"author\\":\\"\\",\\"rights\\":\