(469, 49, 1, '', '2017-09-29 07:53:14', 959, 3153, 'd1e6702eeb936c9a158a089e85f3b428872c7f06', '{"id":49,"asset_id":377,"title":"Gunongan and Taman Putroe Phang","alias":"gunongan-and-taman-putroe-phang","introtext":"<p><span style=\\"font-size: 12pt;\\"><strong>Gunongan and Taman Putroe Phang<\\/strong><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p style=\\"text-align: justify;\\"><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">Gunongan had built by Sultan Iskandar Muda (1607-1636) as a private playground and bathing place for Putroe Phang, the empress of Sultan Iskandar Muda (1607-1636) who made him fall in love when the Sultan and his troops succeeded in conquering the Kingdom of Johor and the Kingdom of Pahang in North Malay Peninsula (Malaya). Gunongan also witnessed the love of Sultan to the empress as the place to play when his empress longed for her homeland in Pahang. In the past, Gunongan was also known as <em>Ghairah <\\/em>Park which was swept with the river of Darul Asyiqi (Isyqi), and there was also a cemetery which became the burial place of Sultan Iskandar Tsani (the son-in-law of Sultan Iskandar Muda) formerly used as a lunch place for the King and his Empress as well as the royal family. This whimsical architectural fantasy had access to the sultan''s palace through the traditional <em>Pintu Aceh <\\/em>(the door of Aceh), passed by royal family only. This building likely functioned as an important recreational place located in Taman Sari Park for the Queen and other royal family members. It is quite enjoyable to visit this place during the late afternoon or sunset.\\u00a0<\\/span><\\/p>","fulltext":"","state":1,"catid":"14","created":"2017-09-29 07:53:14","created_by":"959","created_by_alias":"","modified":"2017-09-29 07:53:14","modified_by":null,"checked_out":null,"checked_out_time":null,"publish_up":"2017-09-29 07:53:14","publish_down":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","images":"{\\"image_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"float_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_caption\\":\\"\\",\\