(483, 24, 1, '', '2017-09-29 09:25:17', 959, 10678, '567e89b6e4ca8d654c89813ddbb3946c0efd778b', '{"id":24,"asset_id":"349","title":"Aceh","alias":"aceh","introtext":"<p><span style=\\"font-size: 12pt;\\"><strong>Aceh<\\/strong><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">Aceh is world famous for bearing the brunt of the worst tsunami in recorded history in the early hours of Boxing Day 2004 in which over 200,000 people died. However, this is the most western of Indonesia\\u2019s provinces that has a long and rich culture. Its strategic position at the most western point of the Indonesian archipelago has made it a trade and cultural gateway between East and West for many centuries. Aceh is often prominently known as a haven for Chinese, European, Indian and Arab traders, where the first cultural and religious value immersed in the archipelago. The name of Aceh is an acronym of Arab, Chinese, European and Hindustan (ACEH).<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 12pt;\\"><strong>Provincial Structure<\\/strong><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p style=\\"text-align: justify;\\"><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">The province of Aceh is the most northern and western province of Indonesia, situated on the northern tip of Sumatra. Its capital city is Banda Aceh. Administratively, Aceh consists of 18 districts, 5 municipalities, 289 subdistricts and 6.474 gampong (villages) with an area of 57.956 km<sup>2<\\/sup>. There is a unity of the legal community within the province consisting of a few <em>gampong <\\/em>that have territorial boundaries with their own property and sub-district called <em>Mukim<\\/em>, for each <em>Mukim<\\/em> led by <em>Imum Mukim <\\/em>(customary leader).<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 12pt;\\"><strong>Geography<\\/strong><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p style=\\"text-align: justify;\\"><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">The province of Aceh is situated in the North of Sumatra, with an area of approximately 57,365 km<sup>2<\\/sup>, or 12.26% of the Sumatra Island. It includes 119 islands, 73 major rivers and 2 lakes. Aceh is surrounded by the Straits of Malacca in the north, North Sumatra Province in the Southeast and the Indian Ocean in the west.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p style=\\"text-align: justify;\\"><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">The center of this westward extansion area is a range of Bukit Barisan and various highlands including Tangse, Gayo and Alas. Besides the cluster of Pase mountains, there are Mount Geurudong (2,295 m), Peuet Sagoe (2,780 m), Burni Telong (2,566 m) and Ucop Mulo (3,187 m). In the Alas mountains, there are Mount Abong (3,015 m) and Leuser (3,466 m). In the mountainous region of Aceh Besar, there are two peaks of Mount Seulawah Agam (1762 m) and Seulawah Inong (868 m).<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p style=\\"text-align: justify;\\"><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">The area also has several lakes such as Lake Laut Tawar in Central Aceh with an area of 60 km<sup>2<\\/sup> and Lake Aneuk Laot in Sabang (Weh Island). There are also several major and lesser rivers, which run into both of Malacca Strait or the Indonesian Ocean. Among the rivers running into Malacca Straits are: Krueng Aceh (Aceh River) in the Greater Aceh Regency, Krueng Peusangan and Krueng Jambo Aye in North Aceh Regency, Krueng Baro in Pidie Regency, and Krueng Peureulak and Krueng Tamiang in East Aceh Regency; The rivers running to the Indonesian Qcean are Krueng Teunom and Krueng Meureubo in West Aceh Regency, Krueng Kluet, Krueng Simpang Kiri and Krueng Simpang Kanan in South Aceh Regency. On the west and south coasts, there are both large and small islands, some of which are inhabited and others, which are uninhabited. These islands are Weh Island, Breuh Island, Nasi Island, Simeulue Island and Tuangke Island.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p style=\\"text-align: justify;\\"><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">There are a number of major towns, among them: Banda Aceh (capital), Lhokseumawe, Meulaboh, Sigli, and Calang. Also the island of Sabang (an hour ferry ride from Banda Aceh) is considered as diver''s and snorkeler''s pristine paradise belongs to the province.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 12pt;\\"><strong>How to get there <\\/strong><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 12pt;\\"><strong>Visa<\\/strong><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p style=\\"text-align: justify;\\"><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">Foreigners no longer require a travel permit (<em>Surat Jalan<\\/em>) to enter Aceh, but an Indonesian visa is required if their country origin is not on the list of 169 Receiving Visa Free Countries. Furthermore, Since 6 June 2010, it is possible to get a 30 days Visa-on-Arrival at Banda Aceh Airport.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<h3><span style=\\"color: #000000; font-size: 12pt;\\">By bus<\\/span><\\/h3>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">There are non-stop night buses depart from Medan to Banda Aceh and it takes 9-13 hours. Major bus companies such as PMTOH, Pelangi, Kurnia and Pusaka have offices on Jl. Gajah Mada, Medan.\\u00a0 The price ranges from Rp 110,000 in a regular-sized-seat bus to Rp 200,000 in a wide-seat bus. Mini-buses can also take you to Banda Aceh from the Medan area. It will cost you a bit cheaper thatn the coaches but the trip are generally longer. It is also possible to depart from Medan to Banda Aceh via Kutacane and Takengon. This will take 20 hours.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 12pt;\\"><strong>By Plane <\\/strong><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">Sultan Iskandar Muda Airport (BTJ) is the name of airport located in the capital of Aceh Province. The Airlines schedule fly daily from Banda Aceh to Medan (1 hour trip) and either Jakarta (2 hours 40 minutes trip) and vice versa.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<ol>\\r\\n<li><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">Air Asia, Banda Aceh-Kuala Lumpur (vice versa) daily flights<\\/span><\\/li>\\r\\n<li><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">Firefly, Malaysia''s community airline now flies from Penang to Banda Aceh every Tuesday, Thursday and Saturday<\\/span><\\/li>\\r\\n<li><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">Garuda Indonesia, Citilink, Lion Air, Batik Air, Jakarta-Banda Aceh (vice versa) daily flights<\\/span><\\/li>\\r\\n<li><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">SMAC, Blang Pidie, Meulaboh, Simelue, Takengon, Tapaktuan. It flies daily from Medan to Nias Island and Simeulue Island.<\\/span><\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ol>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 12pt;\\"><strong>Airport Bus<\\/strong><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p style=\\"text-align: justify;\\">A DAMRI bus provides a service from Banda A\\u0441eh to the airport, and from the airport to Banda Aceh. It has operating hours at 10 a.m - 4.30 p.m and the price to the city is Rp 20,000 per person. The bus departing from the airport to Banda A\\u0441eh leaves a few minutes after the airplanes landing. Therefore, departure time depends on airplanes\\u2019 landing schedule. Thus, it is advised to hurry to catch the bus. It is on your left when you leave the airport building (taxi drivers will tell you there is no airport bus, just keep on walking because the bus is there). Please note that this bus goes to Banda Aceh City Centre, it does not go to the Bus Station or Ulee-Lhue Harbour. If you want to go to the Bus Station or Ulee-Lhue Harbour, take a <em>becak <\\/em>(traditional ground vehicle) after being dropped off in the City Centre by the airport bus. To go to the airport, you can catch the bus at 8 am, 2 pm or 3 pm in front of the Great Mosque of Banda Aceh or Masjid Baiturahman.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 12pt;\\"><strong>By Boat<\\/strong><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p style=\\"text-align: justify;\\"><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">The closest international ferry terminal is Belawan Port, close to Medan. It receives vessels originating from Batam Island. Entourage of tourists can also depart from Ulhee-lhee Port (Banda Aceh) to Weh Island and Aceh Island.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 12pt;\\"><strong>Get Around<\\/strong><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">The main vehicle of getting around are <em>becak<\\/em> (motorbike taxis) and <em>labi-labi<\\/em> (public minibus). Both pblic transportation will cost you, becak fares are Airport - Grand Mosque is Rp 40,000,\\u00a0 Bus Terminal - Grand Mosque is Rp 8,000, Grand Mosque \\u2013 Penayong is Rp 5,000.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: 12pt;\\"><strong>Additional Information<\\/strong><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p style=\\"text-align: justify;\\"><span style=\\"font-size: 10pt;\\">There are approximately 65 NGOs currently operating in Banda Aceh.\\u00a0 However, they generally do not recruit non-Indonesians. These NGOs include various UN and EU agencies, USNS, Care, Americare, Islamic Relief, International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent, Australian Red Cross, Turkish Red Crescent, Kuwaiti Red Crescent, French Red Cross, IMC, IOM, WHO, Japan International Cooperation System, Habitat, Medecins sans fronti\\u00e8res, Japan Platform, USAID. At the peak of the post-Tsunami aid effort there were 850 NGOs, but many of these were non-Muslim religious organisations and their permits were not extended by the Indonesian government.<\\/span><\\/p>","fulltext":"","state":1,"catid":"14","created":"2017-09-29 04:34:18","created_by":"959","created_by_alias":"","modified":"2017-09-29 09:25:17","modified_by":"959","checked_out":"959","checked_out_time":"2017-09-29 09:22:22","publish_up":"2017-09-29 04:34:18","publish_down":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","images":"{\\"image_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"float_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_caption\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"float_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_caption\\":\\"\\"}","urls":"{\\"urla\\":false,\\"urlatext\\":\\"\\",\\"targeta\\":\\"\\",\\"urlb\\":false,\\"urlbtext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetb\\":\\"\\",\\"urlc\\":false,\\"urlctext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetc\\":\\"\\"}","attribs":"{\\"article_layout\\":\\"\\",\\"show_title\\":\\"\\",\\"link_titles\\":\\"\\",\\"show_tags\\":\\"\\",\\"show_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"info_block_position\\":\\"\\",\\"info_block_show_title\\":\\"\\",\\"show_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_associations\\":\\"\\",\\"show_author\\":\\"\\",\\"link_author\\":\\"\\",\\"show_create_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_modify_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publish_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_item_navigation\\":\\"\\",\\"show_icons\\":\\"\\",\\"show_print_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_email_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_vote\\":\\"\\",\\"show_hits\\":\\"\\",\\"show_noauth\\":\\"\\",\\"urls_position\\":\\"\\",\\"alternative_readmore\\":\\"\\",\\"article_page_title\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publishing_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_article_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_backend\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_frontend\\":\\"\\"}","version":2,"ordering":"34","metakey":"","metadesc":"","access":"1","hits":"9","metadata":"{\\"robots\\":\\"\\",\\"author\\":\\"\\",\\"rights\\":\\"\\",\\"xreference\\":\\"\\"}","featured":"0","language":"*","xreference":""}', 0),
